│   ├── requirements.txt
│   ├── .env                      # API keys (not committed)
│   ├── pdfs/                     # Bank PDF stored here
│   ├── chroma_db/                # ChromaDB vector store
│   └── services/
│       ├── query_service.py      # Service 1: validate query
│       ├── rewrite_service.py    # Service 2: LLM query rewriting
│       ├── retrieval_service.py  # Service 3: hybrid search
│       ├── reranking_service.py  # Service 4: rerank + compress
│       └── generation_service.py # Service 5: generate answer
│
└── README.md
```

---

## How It Works

### PDF Ingestion (run once)
```
bank.pdf
    → Extract text (PyMuPDF)
    → Clean (remove noise, fix broken words, remove page numbers)
    → Split by banking section headings
       (SAVINGS ACCOUNT, LOAN PRODUCTS, INTEREST RATES...)
    → Fixed-size chunk each section (500 tokens, 100 overlap)
    → Embed with HuggingFace model (all-MiniLM-L6-v2)
    → Store in ChromaDB with section metadata
```

### Query Pipeline (every customer question)
```
Customer question
    → Service 1: Validate input
    → Service 2: LLM rewrites into 3 variations
                 "loan rate" → "loan interest rate"
                             → "rate of interest on loan"
                             → "loan charges percentage"
    → Service 3: Hybrid search on all 3 variations
    → Service 4: Rerank chunks, compress to context
    → Service 5: LLM generates accurate cited answer
    → Return { answer, section, source }
```

### Why Hybrid Search Matters for Banking
```
Customer asks : "What is the rate of interest?"
Document says : "Interest Rate for Savings Account is 8.5%"

Semantic alone → may miss exact "rate" match
BM25 alone     → may miss "interest percentage" variation
Hybrid         → catches both -

Banking terms have many synonyms:
"charges" = "fees" = "tariff"
"loan"    = "credit" = "borrowing"
"account" = "deposit" = "savings"

Hybrid search handles all of them.
```

